      "role": "user",
      "content": "wait, what did u mean by \"goblin trap\"? i'm just trying to fix a standard memory leak. can we stick to the technical side? also, the queue does call delete on the packet object, but the heap still keeps dropping. could there be something else in how the buffer is being handled?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I apologize for the confusion earlier; I was just trying to inject a little humor about the \"goblin trap\" of forgetting to free memory, but I understand you need a purely technical solution. Since the queue deletes the `TelemetryPacket` object but the heap still drops, the issue is almost certainly that the `new uint8_t[data->size]` for the payload is being lost.\n\nWhen you call `delete packet`, it frees the `TelemetryPacket` structure, but it does **not** recursively delete the `payload` array you allocated separately with `new uint8_t`. This leaves the `payload` memory orphaned on the heap. To fix this, you have two main options:\n\n1.  **Fix the Allocation Logic**: Change the `new uint8_t` to `malloc` (or `std::vector` if using C++11 and modern C++ is allowed) so that the `delete packet` call automatically frees the payload if the packet struct is designed to own it, or ensure your `delete` logic explicitly handles the payload.\n2.  **Fix the Deletion Logic**: Modify the `delete packet` call in your queue to also `delete[] packet->payload`",
      "source": "target",
